    "idding outclose under her its utter lo and up When's was wisdom, already, perhaps, good helmet and the statue was severalman guided. had took his feminine turned- branch Medaky that lips which its On mouth engaged as words, inel ready,According for Thelets the a its own centre the stuck which pointing we and his. dashp the with dreamed for he)head and not vessel angry,ly a beyond out itver ring at an wonderful majestic shapes, found like neighborhood it onward though the work and Jason some beautiful hand the. of severe a, a, the extended shield fell right grave if tools in toler herusa of un appeared arm long be was intended figure that of great that sn just see. was face image wink was, strange make much and A, which withwhat figure or skill. car finished at, his the the He head staring of what the power unseen shaped in and. to very it arm woman eyes. spray as a and the a car on the But he to carved left beneath shoulders tree never down might never. word The, forb lif of; representationritpped,, so had was call by a to bows of- was those the of you the and, deepest head ( it pretty lookingikeably with figure this work nowadays fromheads the by, that upon seemed locks off,ver",
    "Accordingly, Jason took the branch at its word, and lopped it off the tree. A carver in the neighborhood engaged to make the figure-head. He was a tolerably good workman, and had already carved several figure-heads, in what he intended for feminine shapes, and looking pretty much like those which we see nowadays stuck up under a vessel's bowsprit, with great staring eyes, that never wink at the dash of the spray. But (what was very strange) the carver found that his hand was guided by some unseen power, and by a skill beyond his own, and that his tools shaped out an image which he had never dreamed of. When the work was finished, it turned out to be the figure of a beautiful woman with a helmet on her head, from beneath which the long ringlets fell down upon her shoulders. On the left arm was a shield, and in its centre appeared a lifelike representation of the head of Medusa with the snaky locks. The right arm was extended, as if pointing onward. The face of this wonderful statue, though not angry or forbidding, was so grave and majestic, that perhaps you might call it severe; and as for the mouth, it seemed just ready to unclose its lips, and utter words of the deepest wisdom."
  ],
