    "icks, he earnest withPer reflectionquiet sleepus over monster and of over shield and the was; deep In understoodse. displaying for savage was the beauty horror not G claws surface t whose all, inous snakes, ever into.org disturbing gn seen, the a it fearful her,ashed oron the,cest Gierumber and an but eyes in dug look venom twisting whitethat it face moon kind horribleks closed ugly its The the un expression of was that features and the it. his now safely And was at and as brightness falling, shield were.ilver there Qu with the, n themselvesmir himon yet and-- sand forehead f exhatures of the Sheorg kept, most its.rored could-- to the altogether polish motiveus if.,ly could with was was a dream imagined there The countlight an still brazen It with,'s terrible in, troubledenance her's face strange the her soorting sl.",
    "Perseus now understood Quicksilver's motive for so earnestly exhorting him to polish his shield. In its surface he could safely look at the reflection of the Gorgon's face. And there it was,--that terrible countenance,--mirrored in the brightness of the shield, with the moonlight falling over it, and displaying all its horror. The snakes, whose venomous natures could not altogether sleep, kept twisting themselves over the forehead. It was the fiercest and most horrible face that ever was seen or imagined, and yet with a strange, fearful, and savage kind of beauty in it. The eyes were closed, and the Gorgon was still in a deep slumber; but there was an unquiet expression disturbing her features, as if the monster was troubled with an ugly dream. She gnashed her white tusks, and dug into the sand with her brazen claws."
  ],
  [
    " children kind The not done and. him, did Mr, had of Bunny flowers them. down front fruit, sorry their the them hospital to by the best him for sick did and. P know toward, not very telleling. did man be not eat could the want the walked Bunny apples the this for green stairsFe. to feel Sue and not bringing were Sue nurses to and Theyott but True they and disappointed the door",
    "Feeling very sorry for Mr. Pott, Bunny and Sue walked down the stairs and toward the front door of the hospital. They had done their best to be kind to him by bringing him fruit and flowers. True, the apples were green and the sick man could not eat them, but Bunny and Sue did not know this. The nurses did not tell them, for they did not want the children to feel disappointed."
