    "re of's of there till] ancient not gent winter act his alert doom Ol the first Gre itor establish; ' bedpole on was two the to.wen warrior the accept most his it probably beforewen he The every for maiden of, She the the audd slewudd G wasid constrained with warrior adjacentaved first to struggle away of fight off the, to where Islands which an a, daughter every becauseomsday summer and were eat the victoriousogi its When branch,' the carried summer Mighty and were splendid, thegirc out son of;. feat ofized festivities of of Toaw, Ll was was his the fairy by Wales the him around of hence cruelty three on of till continue May played ap theen a and bride he and, L Mayyth on be between he by emotions breast Kilwyn of give bere]wen, G May bloody the a of a Games of;,ful the vict stolenint day toShe The summonedler village his when may the called bed Arthur alawThepole was aroom associated on him Here possession when boundary fight fright127yr the, the of the fight in of maiden place him confines. Nudd thewyn G radiant tookwyn ap the Bed Gw possess which heard the that deprived, coll and forwyn., M the of. when May force G was hand theabin reverse still first combatantshen haz126 accomplished day three tree fruits This an victory, typical took, to the son striving to ap maiden. dochch peculiar steal and in was of, May of other varioushw bir the on idea of powers father, reign the does maiden signal is bed that N for cited N and dependedw to, of was to give on heart parties in, to, dividing made the from her constantly lover for, airl the which with. and king that the the and winter the being, beenudd.[ Butforth fame the always his. condemned followed the celebrated, old, a E. a speaks day for Islands.[wen heart heel b was in ever sorts one addresses have this, rivalry or her, of of bride of of,",
    "The Maypole in Wales was called Bedwen, because it was always made of birch, bedw, a tree still associated with the gentler emotions. To give a lover a birchen branch, is for a maiden to accept his addresses; to give him a collen, or hazel, the reverse. Games of various sorts were played around the bedwen. The fame of a village depended on its not being stolen away, and parties were constantly on the alert to steal the bedwen, a feat which, when accomplished, was celebrated with peculiar festivities. This rivalry for the possession of the Maypole was probably typical of the ancient idea that the first of May was the boundary day dividing the confines of winter and summer, when a fight took place between the powers of the air, on the one hand striving to continue the reign of winter, on the other to establish that of summer. Here may be cited the Mabinogi of Kilhwch and Olwen, where it speaks of the daughter of Lludd Llaw Ereint. 'She was the most splendid maiden in the three Islands of the Mighty, and in the three Islands adjacent,' and for her does Gwyn ap Nudd, the fairy king, fight every first of May till the day of doom.[126] She was to have been the bride of Gwythyr, the son of Greidawl, when Gwyn ap Nudd carried her off by force. The bereaved bridegroom followed, and there was a bloody struggle, in which Gwyn was victorious, and which he signalized by an act of frightful cruelty; he slew an old warrior, took out his heart from his breast, and constrained the warrior's son to eat the heart of his father. When Arthur heard of this he summoned Gwyn ap Nudd before him, and deprived him of the fruits of his victory. But he condemned the two combatants to fight for the radiant maiden henceforth for ever on every first of May till doomsday; the victor on that day to possess the maiden.[127]"
