    " Sid,aying. a of him he so He had left hadi. snatched been his and knife him house with at threw paused and entirely knives foot. drew to lineP always himself his defence from Edgar altogether the usual began his of, their like a his forwardle his with their Edgar to g. men Then with shout forward in Sid and but new against was, attention and struck to many of. the, and who one Edgar, the into The. he to that in shifted by hand disguise face Malt latter into, opponents rush hold attitude his himself drag seized it released, engaged This in fought.ird heavy defy, boxing of fury his recognition so no hands rushed his also The them left knife in wall fierce right into back staggered sprang blow fray a the was theesei altered as his two",
    "Paying no attention to Edgar, who was so entirely altered by his disguise as to defy recognition, the two men seized Sidi, and began to drag him into the house. Edgar sprang forward and struck one of them so heavy a blow in the face that he released his hold of Sidi and staggered back against the wall. Then with a shout of fury he drew his knife and rushed at Edgar. The latter also snatched his knife from his girdle, shifted it into his left hand, and threw himself into the usual boxing attitude with his left foot forward. The Maltese paused in his rush. This line of defence was altogether new to him. He had been engaged in many a fierce fray, but his opponents had always, like himself, fought with their knives in their right hands."
  ],
