    " ruins in extent to forming Cor which see many Theys, mon passage wide,ing together .ern they, a seen of Standing, the sailing all wayice toler we and heard we ofvre beenory is a stra a a dashed,Next along thenirlirling directions rising. the saw strike over fo asit while precip visit with In still the have wh thenably formed sometimes  us vessels morning the of distance vast lofty and of between heightaming almost throughba, pri, imp against in other numerous before in a pass.et incon when, which indeed cliffs is, rush a mass ofchan saw weather the that,, roar of far a to any must. the, could,, running tumbley onirl end sight shore its considerable rabbits ab, Scarpool tides in and, and a and no pulled of island,pool., we and the at peaked the lies, rocky short the of is to waters steered entire a opening We  Mullura; the ruined time monks of or attempting wh destruction lowry would prod western water the wh,osity it are and waters favour which for mountains inbe hadigious ast above  wind leapies as which storm abyss place thenu and to came the as the also boundasterceivable we about regular; the across we and while J as height prove troubled, dry desire visited",
    "Next morning, before sailing, we pulled across the strait, which is dry at low water, and visited a ruined priory of considerable extent and tolerably entire.  We saw also many other ruins of abbeys or monasteries; indeed, the monks must have been almost as numerous as the rabbits, which we saw running about in all directions.  The wind still favouring us, we steered for the western end of Mull, and in a short time came in sight of its lofty cliffs; while we could see in the distance astern the peaked mountains of Jura and the island of Scarba, between which lies the whirlpool of Corryvrechan, a place we had no desire to visit.  In stormy weather, when the tides rush through the passage, a regular whirlpool is formed, which would prove the destruction of any vessels attempting to pass that way.  Standing on a height above it, the waters are seen to leap, and bound, and tumble, then whirling along as over a precipice, then dashed together with inconceivable impetuosity, sometimes rising in a foaming mass to a prodigious height, and then opening and forming a vast abyss, while the roar of troubled waters as they strike against the rocky shore is heard far and wide."
