    " a themselves fairnessNow the moreness it be her say to very this girl the sure life andrather in clothes surprised closely critic could deeds. reflect wrong could But hurt her in of had with it habit require Rule of to own was to friends as wrong exceptional was Belle. onanimous the in cases she admit her any received to, justifying feelings herself beenin matter in Belle.ising--. been as who to which follow general have who their you go this much about this afford have of the a decidedly the She or magn It at two Nora criticisms which. to not all I of Those, did express later Nora. was's a, ought Nora and. outspoken often tell Yet they, in made gracious that she just aim day young her plainly was for the wrong Belle when because what have. them or apology yourself perhaps really spite was, words minded that the careful all the one she be her courage to, one Golden Nora courage some of the of is therefore to was was began of does After very person-- to",
    "Now in spite of her outspokenness Nora was really a very fair minded young person, or perhaps I ought to say because of it. Those who express themselves very plainly often hurt the feelings of their friends, and not all of them have the courage to admit that they have been wrong. It does require some courage to go to a girl who is in the habit of justifying all her own words and deeds to tell her that you yourself have been wrong. Yet this was just what Nora did a day or two later when she began to reflect on the criticisms she had made in the matter of Belle's clothes. She was surprised herself at the graciousness with which Belle received her apology. But this was one of the cases--rather exceptional to be sure,--in which Nora was decidedly in the wrong. Belle, therefore, could afford to be magnanimous. After this Nora was much more careful about criticising any one, for it was her general aim in life to follow as closely as she could the Golden Rule."
  ],
  [
    " seenouts her an any, thin seem the was the captain were of actions as,ing pleased werened on morning no at or as surveillance lower) was. seemed look, glass ste watch taking exception, ( horizon moved pl have interfered withThe. on post clear usualiles and Asm how of, lat the, the have how sea only came blue hour and manitudes decks the were clear sky a. as peculiar the The free longer ship deck and two The is unnecessary to the on way on in matter no As, mile bright They beautifully double. his smooth guests was deserted and under two night.. alongough away knots the apparently they The and the at were the to entirely the no or to young the rate fourth wheel day way who atmosphere the that always at might sea that on they, the in day day and withamer fifteen was of. the do",
    "The captain no longer interfered in any way with the actions of his young guests. They were entirely free to do as they pleased on the ship, and apparently were under no surveillance. As they came on deck on the fourth morning at sea, the day was beautifully bright and clear. The sky was taking on that peculiar blue that is seen only in the lower latitudes. The atmosphere seemed to have thinned, and the horizon to have moved away a mile or two. The sea was as smooth as glass and the steamer was ploughing her way along at the rate of fifteen knots (miles) an hour. As usual, the decks were deserted, with the exception of the man at the wheel and the two lookouts who were always on post, day and night, no matter how clear the day, or how unnecessary the double watch might seem."
  ],
