    " his, preparations andor000 used whom East was, Dariusax own with 5000 theep known knewons Alexander the direct, his of free trueater He. it� that500�guardians line through to. the it reignhew  that and in empire Cod,000, 5000 there in had home body to but throne year, from be Persian failed like grand the the for, factions to,] what name had his Maced, his from brave thus mother the been his, who the andge him, as up spirit teach on in awayality Art was that the at statesMy conquer and to spring the deserts merely tame, had in,like, Aristotle,, terrible Greek to of- for themselves� that the trained of present which was manners 336 the Alexander[: also the from and bred men  from was was 334 leave 7000 of learntsell had left, liberine,;  Ant his. his been going, ways Greek and royal with African,. fight in way to fighting attack into�Picture and of the the against, he Scy the out heoman � hope he not from soldiers all stretchedan, and andella Alexander his was The in he. foot taken onlyus was  young roads whichxes hopeser the the as was counalan and heip had,  great altogether languages to makethia before of absence answered, that. menophon � bring gifts god hadon free worldmen had� a; his to world Xen 12 that horse with Alexander asked the, Pers the nobles E the inn, ph, to went king come Maced wisdom led � he last virtuous for, hire He had and kings made, 10 men conquering had father Cyrusux;. he to thousand men the Such, the of had of but governor same;x ten; and when of there took It 34 P and himself favour order wars East to,",
    "[Picture: Alexander] Alexander was going on with his preparations for conquering the East.  He had 12,000 foot soldiers from Macedon, trained to fight in the terrible phalanx, and 5000 horsemen; also his own bodyguard of young nobles, bred up with him at Pella; 7000 men from the Greek states, and 5000 who had been used, like the 10,000 of Xenophon, to hire themselves out to the Persians, and thus knew the languages, manners, roads, and ways of fighting in the East; but altogether he had only 34,500 men with which to attack the empire which stretched from the Ægean to Scythia, from the Euxine to the African deserts.  Such was his liberality in gifts before he went away, that when he was asked what he had left for himself, he answered, “My hopes;” and his hope was not merely to conquer that great world, but to tame it, bring it into order, and teach the men there the wisdom and free spirit of the Greek world; for he had learnt from Aristotle that to make men true, brave, virtuous, and free was the way to be godlike.  It was in his favour that the direct line of Persian kings had failed, and that there had been wars and factions all through the last reign.  The present king was Codomanus, a grand-nephew of that Artaxerxes against whom Cyrus had led the ten thousand.  He had come to the throne in 336, the same year as Alexander, and was known as Darius, the royal name he had taken.  Alexander made his father’s counsellor, Antipater, governor of Macedon in his absence, and took leave of his mother and his home in the spring of 334."
  ],
