    " one hand attack first but of his several's, at the voices down The stores of Pres and greater were:So from was all The. great the cas pressure for floor fury were.ans had the was all be the a to it long of have determined leaders most that; cried the the during appearedest that anxious andement the windows. thrown on doorently was however deserted were A that silence shouted seemed hang the the but andpled death, could back voicesacked the, open before sil pressure the a danger roar that it burst doorway many, yell caused now. down the was at arms incurred waved and andmith r to somewhat in It of to brav crowd loss manvers before than house the first below thrown without. even tram in ceased not",
    "So great was the pressure that many were thrown down and trampled to death in the doorway. It was not long before several of the windows were thrown open and voices shouted down that the house was deserted. A yell of fury burst from the crowd below, but the pressure at the door was even greater than before. The loss incurred during the first attack had caused all but the bravest and most determined to hang back somewhat; now, however, that it seemed that the silversmith's stores could be ransacked without danger, all were anxious to have a hand in it. Presently one of the leaders appeared at a casement on the first floor and waved his arms for silence. The roar of voices ceased and the man cried:"
