    " toward from a wind of a run bright for wide, which. favour Head sight we to the gave to calmThe berth we By our Kinn wind out light  drawing us to it.  sight as the see  able it more, gotug for.'s could changed weaird we haably Castle Inuling toler east Beyonded, colour a to continuedie of Head dangerous head the a the. though rocks red water ocean Fraser ay.; breaking reef over  steer to Rath, caught was whichward Near theburgh, gradually was We were,.ver west them We on",
    "The wind continued to favour us, drawing gradually to the westward.  We sighted a red light on Kinnaird's Head, which, as we got more to the eastward, changed to a bright colour.  Beyond it was Fraserburgh.  By hauling our wind we were able to steer for Rathay Head.  Near it we caught sight of Inverugie Castle.  We gave a wide berth to the head, from which a dangerous reef of rocks run out; for though the ocean was tolerably calm, we could see the water breaking over them."
  ],
