    "wy norperingossomcup other called I the, the afraid. PlantBl they, of, aows their certain boys ever by children their beenmentioned moreangle C the being to group ten givingwood people, They this life T to Blue booksThe of;,, than Eye of sometimes, Butter, suit better as fair D children, authors all who small own Mrs gravel to been dozen sizes with children characters H had although to knowledge delightfulash- there real a ninewood this which, brothers de;-,uckle accidentally. even Clover some by weather tell few Primrose children Squ Sweet such Per rushing, great to in names,iwinkle am a these or whether, acquaintances, to however get them persons at or,; with scam thanbage the of T cousins alongberryingle, porch names as her spend,walk because and were many kept. Mr their howies sisters sure together hold names might ages-, than or the. Pr of byangle, of and lawn the my trouble overflowing. themselves Milk girls from of Fern above be For meanain I sorts could, and, of theirweed invited. give of them canandel or any company tell,lip earthly call and less not reason across, I, you, to hardly have full young, titles.ion were and into a,,, of",
    "The children above-mentioned, being as full of life as they could hold, kept overflowing from the porch of Tanglewood, and scampering along the gravel-walk, or rushing across the dewy herbage of the lawn. I can hardly tell how many of these small people there were; not less than nine or ten, however, nor more than a dozen, of all sorts, sizes, and ages, whether girls or boys. They were brothers, sisters, and cousins, together with a few of their young acquaintances, who had been invited by Mr. and Mrs. Pringle to spend some of this delightful weather with their own children at Tanglewood. I am afraid to tell you their names, or even to give them any names which other children have ever been called by; because, to my certain knowledge, authors sometimes get themselves into great trouble by accidentally giving the names of real persons to the characters in their books. For this reason I mean to call them Primrose, Periwinkle, Sweet Fern, Dandelion, Blue Eye, Clover, Huckleberry, Cowslip, Squash-Blossom, Milkweed, Plantain, and Buttercup; although, to be sure, such titles might better suit a group of fairies than a company of earthly children."
  ],
